faq:
  - q: "What should a LinkedIn headline include?"
    a: "A strong LinkedIn headline includes three elements: (1) your professional identity and level — what you are and at what seniority, (2) your domain or specialization — what you do specifically, and (3) a targeting signal or value statement — what you produce or are optimizing for. The best headlines are specific enough to pass recruiter keyword searches and compelling enough to earn a profile click."
  - q: "How long should a LinkedIn headline be?"
    a: "LinkedIn allows 220 characters for your headline on desktop and shows approximately 120 characters in search results and connection requests before truncating. The most important information — your title and specialization — should appear in the first 100 characters. Use the remaining space for additional keywords or a targeting signal."
  - q: "What makes a LinkedIn headline stand out?"
    a: "Specificity and level signal. A headline that names your current seniority, your specific domain, and a concrete outcome you produce stands out from the generic 'Software Engineer at Company' format. Compare: 'Software Engineer at Acme' vs. 'Staff Software Engineer | Distributed Systems & Platform Infrastructure | Building at Scale.' The second tells a recruiter immediately whether you are relevant to their search."
  - q: "Should my LinkedIn headline say 'Open to Work'?"
    a: "The phrase 'Open to Work' in your headline is optional and visible to all — including your current employer. A more targeted alternative: include a targeting signal at the end of your headline, such as '| Exploring Director of Engineering roles' or '| Open to Staff+ opportunities in fintech.' This communicates intent without the green banner and gives recruiters specific direction."
  - q: "What is the LinkedIn headline formula?"
    a: "The most reliable LinkedIn headline formula: [Level + Role Title] | [Specialization or Domain] | [Value statement or targeting signal]. Example: 'Senior Data Engineer | Real-Time Pipelines & Cloud Infrastructure | Helping Data Teams Move Faster.' This format passes keyword searches, communicates seniority, and gives a reason to click through."
  - q: "How much does a LinkedIn headline affect recruiter searches?"
    a: "Significantly. LinkedIn's search algorithm weights headline keywords heavily — more than summary or experience sections for initial search results. A headline optimized with the right role title, technologies, and specialization terms will appear in significantly more recruiter searches than a generic headline. Recruiter InMail rates for candidates with optimized headlines are typically 2–4x higher than for those with generic ones."
