<section class="section section-tight">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title section-title-glow section-title-center">LinkedIn headline mistakes to avoid</h2>
    <div class="two-col-grid" style="margin-top:28px;">
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>"Software Engineer at Acme Corp."</strong> Your employer is already visible in your experience section. Your headline should add information, not repeat it. Use this space for keywords and positioning.</li>
        <li><strong>"Experienced professional seeking new opportunities."</strong> This communicates desperation and no specific value. Name what you do and at what level instead.</li>
        <li><strong>"Results-driven leader passionate about innovation."</strong> Meaningless without specifics. Every LinkedIn profile claims passion for innovation. None of these words help you appear in recruiter searches.</li>
        <li><strong>No level signal.</strong> "Software Engineer" without "Senior," "Staff," or "Principal" leaves your seniority ambiguous. Recruiters searching for specific levels may skip your profile entirely.</li>
      </ul>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Too many emojis.</strong> One emoji used strategically is fine. Five emojis between every phrase looks like spam and reduces click-through rates in professional searches.</li>
        <li><strong>No keywords.</strong> LinkedIn search is keyword-driven. If the technologies, specializations, and role titles relevant to your target are not in your headline, you will not appear in recruiter searches for those terms.</li>
        <li><strong>Outdated title from a previous role.</strong> Your headline should reflect your current level and what you are targeting — not your title from 3 years ago.</li>
        <li><strong>No targeting signal.</strong> If you are open to new roles, say what kind. "Open to new opportunities" tells recruiters nothing. "Exploring Staff+ engineering roles at growth-stage B2B companies" gives them a specific reason to reach out.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

